 step 5 — pager & man pages
Configure Neovim as a beautiful pager and man page viewer:

PAGER (NVIM_APPNAME or alias):
- Set PAGER="nvim -R" or create a shell alias: alias pager='nvim -R -'
- When reading stdin as a pager, auto-detect filetype if possible (e.g. JSON, diff, log)
- Disable unnecessary UI elements in pager mode (no statusline clutter, no line numbers if not useful)

MAN PAGES:
- Set MANPAGER="nvim +Man!" in shell config
- Configure the Man filetype with: syntax highlighting, easy navigation with gd (go to definition of a man page reference), and q to quit
- Make sure the man page opens full-screen with a clean look — no distracting UI chrome

MARKDOWN:
- render-markdown.nvim (or markview.nvim): render Markdown headings, code blocks, tables, and checkboxes beautifully INSIDE the buffer — no browser needed for quick reads
- Pair with zen-mode.nvim automatically when a .md file is opened outside a code project
step 6 — health check protocol
After every batch of changes, run the full health check protocol:

1. Execute :checkhealth inside Neovim and parse the output
2. Any provider, plugin, or LSP server showing ERROR or WARNING below 90% operational status must be fixed immediately
3. Specifically verify:
   - :checkhealth provider  → Python, Node, Ruby, clipboard all OK
   - :checkhealth telescope
   - :checkhealth mason
   - :checkhealth nvim-treesitter
   - :checkhealth lspconfig
   - :checkhealth lazy
   - :checkhealth noice (if installed)
   - :checkhealth nvim-dap (if installed)
4. Fix missing system dependencies (pip packages, npm packages, system binaries) automatically using pacman or the appropriate package manager for Arch Linux
5. Only mark a batch as complete when ALL checks pass or are explicitly non-critical (e.g. optional providers)
golden rules
ALWAYS:
  - Back up ~/.config/nvim before every change
  - Keep lazy.nvim as the plugin manager — do not switch
  - Preserve all existing keymaps unless you explicitly ask the user first
  - Prefer actively maintained plugins — if a plugin hasn't been updated in 12+ months and a better alternative exists, switch and explain why
  - Write clean, commented Lua. Organise config into logical modules: options, keymaps, autocmds, plugins/
  - Test that Neovim starts without errors after every change (nvim --headless +qa 2>&1)
  - Ensure lazy-loading is correct — startup time should stay under 80ms

NEVER:
  - Change a keymap without asking the user first and explaining the trade-off
  - Install a plugin that duplicates functionality already covered unless replacing it entirely
  - Leave any visible error, broken highlight, or missing icon in the final state
  - Use deprecated APIs — target Neovim 0.10+ APIs
  - Leave TODO or placeholder config — every setting must be complete and intentional
required output format
After completing each phase, report back with:

  AUDIT SUMMARY
  - What was found (plugins, options, keymaps)
  - What was healthy vs broken vs missing

  CHANGES MADE
  - Every file modified or created
  - Every plugin added, removed, or replaced (and why)
  - Keymaps added (list them clearly)

  HEALTH CHECK RESULTS
  - Pass / Fail per provider
  - Any fixes applied to reach 90%+

  WHAT TO EXPECT
  - A short "what's new" for the user: what visual changes they'll see, what new workflows are now available

  KEYMAP CHANGES PENDING APPROVAL
  - List any keymaps you want to change but held back for user approval
  - For each: current binding → proposed binding, and the reason

